===Etymology 1===

{{etyl|enm}} {{term|penne|penne||lang=enm}} "enclosure for animals" from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|penn|penn-||lang=ang}} (in compounds) "enclosure" from {{proto|Germanic|penn-|to bolt, pin, nail, secure|lang=en}} from {{proto|Indo-European|bend-|pointed peg, nail, edge|lang=en}}. Akin to {{ang}} {{term|pennian|-pennian||lang=ang}} (in compounds) "to close, lock, bolt" (compare {{term|onpennian|onpennian||lang=ang}} "to open"), {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|pennen|pennen|to secure a door with a bolt|lang=nds}}, {{ang}} {{term|pinn|pinn|peg, bolt|lang=ang}}. More at [[pin]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An [[enclose]]d area used to contain [[domesticated]] animals, especially [[sheep]] or [[cattle]].
#: ''There are two steers in the third '''pen'''.''
# A place to confine a person; a prison cell.
#: ''They caught him with a stolen horse, and he wound up in the '''pen''' again.''
# {{baseball}} The [[bullpen]].
#: ''Two righties are up in the '''pen'''.''

